description.value: Corroded iron large knife, with a wide leaf-shaped blade and a narrow tang with rectangular cross-section, ending with a flattened circular or semi-circular pommel. Traces of the wooden haft are visible on the rusted surface of the tang and the base of the blade. The haft's head was rounded and partly covering the base of the blade on both sides, where the handle slabs were fastened by three nonaligned rivets. Two other rivets were fixing the slabs on the tang, one still protruding on one side. The haft had certainly a shape splaying near the blade.

description.value: Ripple flaked fish-tail knife made from pale pinkish flint. The so-called ripple appearance is produced by pressure flaking using a bone, antler or ivory shank to press off long, thin, shallow, regular parallel flakes across both faces of the piece. The edges are additionally retouched with minute removals pressed off to create finely serrated edges. This represents high quality artisanship on a prestigious piece that may not have functioned as tool but as ceremonial object. The edges are thin, sharp and show no damage or indications of use.

description.value: Ripple flaked knife made from fine grained, pale pink flint. One face modified, the opposite face unmodified and smooth. The upper face is skillfully dressed by pressure flaking using a bone, antler or ivory shank to press off thin, regular, parallel flakes diagonally across the face producing the so-called rippled appearance. This technique requires considerable skill and experience. It is also time-consuming and adds nothing to the functionality of the piece as a tool. Additional tiny, pressure flaked retouch removals occur around the convex edge producing a fine serration and coverging to the offset point of the convex and straight edges. The straight edge is bifacialy modified with tiny, regular scalar removals along the margin of the plane face. The piece is fresh and shows no use damage.

description.value: Small knob made of calcite in a flat cone shape. The base is flat and well smoothed and has a central depression with a diameter of 1.3 cm. In the centre a perforation with a diameter of 0.4 that widens at the upper side to 1.1 cm, the hole was probably drilled only from the upper side, few dark remains of a darker substance in this depression. The upper side is slightly convex, the edge towards the base is rounded and some cut marks are visible from shaping the object. The upper side is smoothed but not as well as the base.

description.value: Limestone fragment: this fragment in the shape of a rounded knob has the prenomen and nomen of Ramses III deeply incised on its face. This piece is composed of two separate fragments which entered the collection at different times and have been joined together. Part of the left edge is still lacking. The polished surface has worn thin on the base of the object and on the right edge of the face. Traces of inlay whose colour has now faded can be seen in certain hieroglyphs.

description.value: Knob-shaped object made of fine brown Nile clay. The base is round and very flat, it was pressed onto a flat surface to form it. The upper side shows a central area that is raised with concave sides running upwards from the base and forms a cylindrical part with a shallow indentation in the middle to attach another object. The depth of this indentation is 0.9 cm, it has a diameter of 1.4 cm and the wall around it is 0.5 cm wide with an outer diameter of 2.2-2.3 cm for the central raised part. The base is partly chipped off, partly was it not formed perfectly round. Some sort of stand or knob. Some white accretion on the surface.

legal.credit_line: © The Trustees of the British Museum

description.value: Relatively thick clay disc-shaped of brown fine Nile clay with mica as inclusions. The underside is flat but slightly convex, the upper side is flat with a central enhancement, partly quite eroded. In the surface around the raised part many small holes were impressed into the clay in several oval clusters. The edges of the clay disc are rounded. The function of this object is not clear, maybe it was used as a lid? The thickness, the heavy weights as well as the decoration might suggest another function.
